taxonomy_info.title: Flexibility & Option Communication
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of explaining program flexibility and customization options in ways that empower student choice.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants present options and flexibility as advantages while maintaining clear program structure.
examples: Consultant: "You have the flexibility to choose between 1 and 4 units per trimester, depending on your other commitments"
Consultant: "In terms of study, we estimate about 16 hours per week per unit. So it's quite flexible – you can do your study whenever suits you"
Consultant: "You can choose psychology units as part of your elective units, which gives you that interdisciplinary approach you're looking for"

taxonomy_info.title: Decision Anxiety & Procrastination Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns related to starting new jobs, career transitions, or general decision-making anxiety that creates hesitation about enrollment timing.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where students express anxiety about major life changes, starting new positions, or feeling overwhelmed by the decision-making process.
examples: Student: "I'm starting a new job next month and I'm not sure how that will affect my ability to study."
Consultant: "Starting a new job is a significant transition. Let's talk about how our flexible program structure could accommodate this change in your work situation"
Student: "I keep going back and forth on this decision. I'm worried about making the wrong choice."
Consultant: "It's natural to feel uncertain about important decisions like this. What specific aspects are creating the most concern for you?"

taxonomy_info.title: Strategic Verification Technique
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of using focused questions to verify understanding of key points and confirming important details without excessive checking.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who employ strategic verification that maintains momentum while ensuring sufficient mutual understanding.
examples: Consultant: "Is there a particular reason you're thinking about pushing that back?"
Consultant: "Just to confirm, when you say flexible, you're mainly referring to scheduling rather than content, correct?"
Consultant: "Let me make sure I understand - your main concern is about the time commitment rather than the subject matter itself?"

taxonomy_info.title: Fee Affordability Concern Resolution
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing direct cost concerns through acknowledgment, exploration of specific financial barriers, and presentation of available payment options without making unverified claims.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants responding to explicit statements about program cost being too expensive, concerns about affordability, or budget constraints.
examples: Student: "And the cost is around $60,000? That's a lot of money. I'm not sure if I can afford that."

Consultant: "I understand your concern about the cost - it is a significant investment. May I ask what specific aspects of the cost are most concerning to you? Is it the total amount, or more about the timing of payments?"
Consultant: "The good news is that we offer FEE-HELP for eligible students, which means you won't need to pay anything upfront and will only begin repayments once your income exceeds the threshold"

taxonomy_info.title: Adaptive Collaboration Style
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of adjusting the level of directiveness versus collaboration based on the student's demonstrated communication preferences and decision-making style.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants adapt their approach to match student signals about preference for guidance versus independent decision-making.
examples: Consultant: "Would you prefer to explore the options together, or would you like me to make a specific recommendation based on your situation?"
Consultant: "I can see you like to think through decisions carefully. Let me outline the options and give you time to consider them"
Consultant: "You seem ready to move forward. Based on everything you've shared, here's what I'd recommend..."

taxonomy_info.title: Circumstance-Specific Solution Co-Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of working with students to develop tailored approaches that address their unique life circumstances, constraints, and goals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who engage students as active participants in creating solutions rather than imposing predetermined approaches.
examples: Consultant: "Based on your caring responsibilities, let's work together to identify which study patterns would be most sustainable for you"
Consultant: "Understanding your financial situation, let's explore which payment and study load combinations would work best"
Consultant: "Given your career transition goals, what timeline feels realistic to you, and how can we structure the program to support that?"

taxonomy_info.title: Mutual Responsibility Establishment
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of creating explicit agreements about both student and consultant responsibilities with clear timelines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who clearly state what they will do and what the student should do, with specific deadlines for both parties.
examples: Consultant: "For now, I will send you the letter fall for very soon to your name in the next five minutes confirming your place in the course"
Consultant: "I'll email you the program guide by 5pm today, and if you can review these by Thursday and send your transcript by Friday, I'll process your application immediately"
Consultant: "Here's what we'll do next: I'll send you the checklist today, you review it by Wednesday, and I'll call you Thursday to finalize everything"

taxonomy_info.title: Responsive Adaptability
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of showing appropriate responsiveness to meaningful student signals and adjusting approach based on clear student cues without overreacting to minor signals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants demonstrate reasonable responsiveness to student signals while balancing structure with flexibility in response to student cues.
examples: Consultant: "I notice you hesitated when I mentioned the group work component. Would you like me to explain more about how that works?"
Consultant: "And in terms of your motivation to do this course, what was it that really sparked your interest in pursuing this one?"
Consultant: "You seem to have some specific questions about the online format. What aspects would be most helpful for me to clarify?"

taxonomy_info.title: Technical Translation Ability
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of translating specialized terminology or complex concepts into accessible language that builds understanding.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who make complex information accessible through clear definitions, comparisons, and practical connections.
examples: Consultant: "A Graduate Certificate is a postgraduate qualification that consists of four units and serves as the first stage of a Master's program. It's classified as AQF Level 8, the same academic level as a Graduate Diploma but half the length"
Consultant: "Let me explain the difference between citizenship options for financial aid. As an Australian citizen, you can access HECS-HELP which means no upfront payments..."
Consultant: "The census date is the last day you can withdraw from a unit without financial or academic penalty. You have until this date to decide if you want to continue"

taxonomy_info.title: Adaptive Communication Style
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of adjusting communication complexity and pace based on student signals and responses.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants modify their approach, repeat information differently, or adjust detail level based on student cues.
examples: Consultant: "Let me break this down differently" (after student confusion)
Consultant: "I can see this is a lot of information. Would you like me to focus on the most important points first?"
Consultant: "Since you mentioned your technical background, you might appreciate that this program uses industry-standard frameworks"
Consultant: "Would you like me to go over the program structure more slowly?"

taxonomy_info.title: Enrollment Process Ambiguity
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant fails to clearly explain the steps required to complete enrollment, particularly related to the Hub and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for vague descriptions of next steps or failure to provide specific guidance about the Hub navigation or account setup requirements.
examples: Consultant: "You'll get an email with everything you need" (without specific guidance)
Consultant fails to explain the distinct steps of creating an account, accessing the Hub, and completing enrollment
Consultant doesn't clearly explain which documents are needed and by when

taxonomy_info.title: Comprehension Checking Technique
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of verifying student understanding through strategic questions and clarification offers.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who use effective checking questions and create opportunities for students to confirm understanding.
examples: Consultant: "Does that make sense to you?" or "Is that clear?"
Consultant: "What questions do you have about the entry requirements?"
Consultant: "Just to make sure we're on the same page, what's your understanding of the academic requirements?"
Consultant: "Should I slow down as I explain these financial details?"

taxonomy_info.title: Selective Content Mirroring
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of selectively mirroring the most important elements of student statements using key terms while maintaining conversation flow.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who acknowledge key concerns using some of the student's own words and demonstrate understanding through focused reflection without creating redundant conversation loops.
examples: Consultant: "Okay great so to open up more doors for you into another career"
Consultant: "So what I'm hearing is you're looking to transition from your current role and work with people in a different capacity"
Consultant: "You mentioned that flexibility is important to you, particularly with your work schedule"

taxonomy_info.title: Contextual Connection Making
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of connecting immediate concerns to previously shared context and integrating key background elements without extensive synthesis.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants thoughtfully incorporate relevant context to demonstrate understanding without creating elaborate frameworks.
examples: Consultant: "Based on what you mentioned earlier about your nursing background, this program would build perfectly on your existing clinical experience"
Consultant: "Given your concern about work-life balance that you shared, let me explain how our flexible structure specifically addresses that"
Consultant: "Connecting this back to your goal of leadership roles that you mentioned, this qualification would position you well for those opportunities"

taxonomy_info.title: Work-Study Integration Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of collaboratively developing specific strategies for balancing work commitments with study requirements, tailored to the student's unique professional circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants work with students to create practical approaches for managing their specific work patterns alongside educational commitments.
examples: Consultant: "With your rotating shifts at the hospital, let's look at how our asynchronous learning format could work with your unpredictable schedule"
Consultant: "Given your travel requirements for work, we should discuss which program features would support you when you're away from home"
Consultant: "Let's map out how the required qualifications and experience needed for your chosen career path align with your current situation"

taxonomy_info.title: Complexity Reduction Strategies
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant breaks down the enrollment process into manageable steps, reducing perceived complexity.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for segmentation of tasks, prioritization of immediate actions, and efforts to make complex processes appear more manageable.
examples: Consultant: "Let's focus on just the first step today: creating your account"
Consultant provides a numbered or sequenced explanation of the process
Consultant distinguishes between essential immediate actions and secondary steps

taxonomy_info.title: Cost Omission or Minimization
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant obscures, minimizes, or fails to fully disclose all costs associated with the program.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for incomplete cost discussions, particularly when a student specifically asks about finances. Note if the consultant focuses only on initial costs without mentioning total program cost.
examples: Consultant discusses per-unit cost but not total qualification cost
Student: "Are there any other fees?" → Consultant: "Nothing significant"
Consultant emphasizes deferred payment without clearly explaining eventual repayment obligations

taxonomy_info.title: Timeline/Deadline Imprecision
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides incorrect or vague information about critical deadlines or program start dates.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where specific dates are requested but not provided, or where the consultant gives incorrect timeline information.
examples: Student: "When is the enrollment deadline?" → Consultant: "Oh, you have plenty of time" (without specifics)
Consultant provides incorrect census date information
Consultant doesn't make clear the consequences of missing key deadlines

taxonomy_info.title: Browsing Without Intent Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing situations where students are exploring options without clear enrollment intent, focusing on moving them toward decision-making clarity.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants responding to students who indicate they're "just looking," comparing multiple options, or not ready to commit to enrollment discussions.
examples: Student: "I'm just browsing at the moment, not really ready to make any decisions."
Consultant: "I appreciate you being upfront about that. Even when browsing, it's helpful to understand what specific information would be most valuable for your decision-making process"

Consultant: "That's completely understandable. Many students benefit from having all the information before they're ready to decide. What aspects of the program are most important for you to understand?"

taxonomy_info.title: Context-Informed Planning Initiation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of using previously gathered information about the student's background, goals, and preferences to guide planning discussions without repetitive questioning.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who reference earlier conversation elements when initiating planning discussions and build on established context rather than starting from scratch.
examples: Consultant: "Based on what you've shared about your work schedule and career goals, let's explore how we might structure your study approach"
Consultant: "Given your nursing background that you mentioned and your interest in leadership roles, there are a couple of pathways we should consider"
Consultant: "You've told me about your rotating shifts and family commitments, so let's look at options that would work with those realities"

taxonomy_info.title: Sequential Step Articulation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of breaking down enrollment processes into specific, numbered steps with clear deadlines and consequences.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who provide structured, step-by-step guidance with specific dates and clear consequences for action/inaction.
examples: Consultant: "Now you will need to set up your Monash account before the 21st of June and you need to select your units before the 22nd of June. If that's not done, you are unenrolled from your course"
Consultant: "Let me outline our three-step application process: 1. Submit your transcript by Friday, 2. Complete the online form by Tuesday, 3. We'll have a brief call next Wednesday"
Consultant: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."

taxonomy_info.title: Structured Eligibility Explanation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of organizing qualification criteria and entry requirements in clear, logical sequences that build understanding.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who present requirements using clear structure, confident language, and appropriate authority without being intimidating.
examples: Consultant: "So to gain entry into this course you have to be diploma qualified so you must hold your diploma of early childhood education and on top of that you need five years of working as room leader or above within the last seven years"
Consultant: "Let me outline the three requirements: first your bachelor's degree, second your work experience, and third your citizenship documentation"
Consultant: "Your experience is definitely valuable. Our program requires the complete 12-month journey to ensure all students develop the skills needed for professional recognition"

taxonomy_info.title: Pathway Clarification Technique
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of explaining alternative routes or non-standard pathways in structured, solution-oriented ways.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants organize pathway information clearly and build confidence about alternative options.
examples: Consultant: "Now with the completed diploma you can't get straight into the Bachelor of Laws program but we do have a great pathway option... an undergraduate certificate which is four bachelor level law units"
Consultant: "While you don't meet the direct entry requirements, let me explain the pathway that gets you to the same destination"
Consultant: "Your previous study can be credited toward the program. Here's exactly how that pathway works..."

taxonomy_info.title: Follow-Up Scheduling Behavior
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of establishing specific dates, times, and methods for follow-up interactions that maintain enrollment momentum.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants schedule specific follow-up calls or interactions with clear purposes rather than leaving contact open-ended.
examples: Consultant: "I'll call you this Friday at 3pm to check on your document progress and answer any questions"
Consultant: "Let's schedule our next call for [date and time]. Does that work for you?"
Consultant: "Would you be looking to study this this year? I'll keep that one active then" (negative example - lacks specific follow-up)

taxonomy_info.title: Urgency & Momentum Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of creating appropriate urgency around enrollment actions while connecting to specific benefits or deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who create time-sensitive motivation through real deadlines, benefits of early action, or consequences of delay.
examples: Consultant: "Following this timeline ensures we complete everything before the May 20th deadline and gives you priority access to unit selection"
Consultant: "Since you're asking about payment options, it sounds like you're thinking seriously about moving forward. The May 5th intake still has places available"
Consultant: "Enrolling today ensures you'll have full access to orientation materials two weeks before classes start"

taxonomy_info.title: Confident Financial Explanation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of presenting financial information with clarity and reassurance, focusing on the most pressing concerns while maintaining transparency.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who address financial anxiety through straightforward, confident language and clear structure.
examples: Consultant: "Bachelor degrees are supported by the Australian HECS loan system, so you don't have to pay out of pocket. As long as you've applied for that student loan, then you won't have to pay out of pocket"
Consultant: "Let me clarify the payment options available to you: FEE-HELP allows you to defer payments, or you can pay upfront before the census date"
Consultant: "I understand cost is a concern. While our investment is higher than Program X, we include benefits that often come as extra costs elsewhere"

taxonomy_info.title: Value Proposition Reinforcement Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of strengthening program value when students express both price concerns and value recognition, connecting institutional strengths to student benefits without fabricating statistics.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where students acknowledge program quality while expressing cost hesitation, creating opportunities to reinforce value before addressing price objections.
examples: Student: "You're more expensive than others I've looked at, but I think University X is the one to go with because it'll be well-recognized."

Consultant: "You've identified exactly what makes our program valuable. We have triple crown accreditation and the second-best business faculty in the country. This recognition translates directly to stronger employment outcomes"
Student: "That's a little bit way beyond our budget."
Consultant: "I understand the investment concern. Let me highlight how our exclusive industry partnerships and comprehensive support often provide value that justifies the investment"

taxonomy_info.title: Flexible Timeline Development
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of collaboratively planning study timelines and teaching period selections that accommodate the student's personal and professional circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants work with students to determine optimal timing for enrollment and progression rather than pushing predetermined schedules.
examples: Consultant: "Let's think about your work project timeline and when you'd feel most ready to take on study commitments"
Consultant: "With your current circumstances, would starting in July or November align better with your other commitments?"
Consultant: "Based on your goals and constraints, let's map out a timeline that feels achievable for your situation"

taxonomy_info.title: Artificial Urgency Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant creates false time pressure or uses scarcity tactics to push for immediate enrollment.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for statements suggesting limited spots, imminent deadlines, or other time pressures that may not be accurate or relevant.
examples: Consultant: "We only have a few spots left in this intake"
Consultant: "I'd hate for you to miss out if you wait too long to decide"
Consultant creates arbitrary deadlines: "I need your decision by tomorrow"

taxonomy_info.title: Teaching Period Selection Objection Response
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about recommended start dates or teaching period timing through explanation of benefits and exploration of alternatives within actual program structure.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where students express disappointment or concern about suggested start dates or timing recommendations.
examples: Student: "I was hoping to start in February, but it sounds like you're suggesting I wait until July. That's a long time to wait, and I'm concerned about losing momentum."
Consultant: "I understand your concern about the timing. Let me explain why July might actually work better for your situation and explore if there are any alternatives that align with your goals"
Consultant: "You can enroll now and defer to the next teaching period if needed, giving you flexibility while securing your place"

taxonomy_info.title: Support Mechanism Integration
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of appropriately introducing relevant post-enrollment support services as part of the planning process while maintaining clear boundaries about the consultant's role.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who position support services as part of the overall educational plan while clarifying that specialized support comes from dedicated post-enrollment teams.
examples: Consultant: "After enrollment, our Student Coaches can help you develop detailed weekly study schedules that work with your rotating shifts"
Consultant: "Let me connect you with one of our student support reps who is clued up on this detail. How does this sound?"
Consultant: "Our Online Learning Advisors specialize in helping students create study approaches for complex work situations like yours"

taxonomy_info.title: Document Requirement Clarity
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant clearly explains all required documentation, submission methods, and deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific, comprehensive information about required documents and submission processes.
examples: Consultant provides a complete list: "You'll need to submit your transcript, ID, and proof of residency"
Consultant explains format requirements: "They'll accept scanned copies or clear photos of your documents"
Consultant discusses deadlines: "To secure your spot in this intake, we need these documents by [specific date]"

taxonomy_info.title: Time Commitment Misalignment
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides inaccurate or incomplete information about the required weekly time commitment for the course.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific hourly estimates provided by the consultant versus student's stated availability. Note discrepancies where the consultant minimizes the actual workload or fails to address obvious conflicts with the student's schedule.
examples: Consultant: "You'll probably just need a few hours each week" (when program actually requires 10-15 hours per unit)
Student: "I work 50 hours a week" → Consultant: "That won't be a problem with our flexible learning"
Consultant fails to discuss specific time requirements when student mentions multiple commitments

taxonomy_info.title: Collaborative Action Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of creating clear, specific next steps with appropriate student input rather than imposing predetermined paths, ensuring mutual ownership of decisions.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants develop action plans that include both consultant and student responsibilities with clear timelines and mutual agreement.
examples: Consultant: "So our plan is: I'll send you the detailed program information today, you'll review it by Thursday, and we'll have another call Friday to finalize your approach. Does that timeline work for you?"
Consultant: "Based on our discussion, you'll start with 2 units in your first teaching period, and we'll evaluate how that's working after the first month. Are you comfortable with that approach?"

Consultant: "Let's agree on next steps: you'll speak with your employer about study support, I'll prepare the enrollment information tailored to what we've discussed, and we'll reconvene next week. Sound good?"

taxonomy_info.title: Autonomy Respect & Confirmation
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of honoring the student's decision-making authority while providing expert guidance, confirming mutual understanding and satisfaction with collaborative plans.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who check for agreement and satisfaction with collaborative decisions while respecting the student's ultimate choice authority.
examples: Consultant: "Does this approach address your concerns about balancing work and study? I want to make sure this feels right for your situation"
Consultant: "We've outlined several options - which approach feels most comfortable to you, or do you need more time to think it through?"
Consultant: "I want to make sure this plan we've developed together feels achievable and exciting to you. How are you feeling about it?"

taxonomy_info.title: Realistic Expectation Setting
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides balanced, honest information about program challenges and benefits, particularly when addressing student concerns.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where the consultant acknowledges both positive and challenging aspects of the program, especially when directly asked.
examples: Consultant: "Many students do find the first unit challenging while adjusting to online study"
Consultant honestly discusses workload demands when asked
Consultant explains both the benefits and limitations of support services

taxonomy_info.title: Immediate Action Triggering
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant successfully encourages specific, immediate post-call actions that initiate the enrollment process.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where the consultant secures commitment to specific actions immediately following the call, rather than general or future-oriented commitments.
examples: Consultant: "While we're on the call, I'll send you the email link. Can you check your inbox and confirm you've received it?"
Consultant establishes specific timing: "Will you be able to create your account this evening?"
Consultant and student agree on specific actions with immediate timeframes

taxonomy_info.title: Assumptive Teaching Period Closing
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of using calendar information as a springboard to secure commitment to a specific teaching period rather than merely providing dates.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for consultants who transition from providing start dates to seeking commitment with phrases like "Were you looking to commence in July?" or "Would [start date] work with your timeline?" followed by documentation requests.
examples: Consultant: "The next intake begins July 7th. Were you looking to commence in July? Great, then I'd just need your transcript and citizenship proof by June 10th."
Consultant: "We have our next intake commencing on the 30th of June. So yeah, today or over the weekend, if you can respond to my email with the document"
Consultant: "Would July work with your timeline? Perfect, to move forward with the July intake, I'll need [documents]"

taxonomy_info.title: Objection Dismissal/Minimization
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant quickly dismisses or minimizes legitimate student concerns rather than addressing them substantively.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where student concerns are downplayed, redirected, or dismissed without adequate exploration or resolution.
examples: Student: "I'm worried about the time commitment" → Consultant: "Oh, everyone feels that way at first, it's no big deal"
Consultant changes the subject when student raises concerns
Consultant provides generic reassurance without addressing the specific concern

taxonomy_info.title: Step-by-Step Guidance Provision
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant provides clear, specific instructions for completing the enrollment process, particularly regarding Hub navigation and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note detailed explanations of enrollment steps, account creation procedures, and Hub navigation that leave little room for confusion.
examples: Consultant explains exact steps: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."
Consultant confirms understanding: "Does that make sense? Can I clarify anything about these steps?"
Consultant anticipates common challenges: "Some people find that section confusing, so let me explain..."

taxonomy_info.title: Proactive Follow-Up Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant establishes specific plans for follow-up communication to support the student through enrollment steps.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note concrete plans for future contact, specific timing, and clear ownership of next steps.
examples: Consultant: "I'll follow up with you next Tuesday to see how you're progressing with your application"
Consultant establishes accountability: "So you'll submit those documents by Friday, and I'll call on Monday to confirm receipt"
Consultant provides direct contact information: "If you have any questions before then, you can reach me at..."

taxonomy_info.title: Appropriate Acknowledgment Depth
taxonomy_info.description: Consultant demonstrates behavior of providing sufficient acknowledgment of student concerns with moderate reflection that validates their experience without overanalyzing.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where consultants provide targeted, specific acknowledgment that clearly demonstrates understanding while maintaining forward progress in the conversation.
examples: Consultant: "Yeah, absolutely. You can take up to six deferrals throughout the master program if need be. You're more than welcome to take several study breaks"

Consultant: "I think even the best students, you know, with balancing work and family as well, would find it difficult here and there. It's always a challenge, no matter how good your work ethic is, so yeah, that's completely understandable"
Consultant: "But it's absolutely understandable being nervous about online study"
